, the book describes how needs were assessed and understood, how evidence-based services were put in place, and the training and education programmes that were developed to assist first those communities affected by the bombing and later the wider population affected by the years of conflict. The author places the mental-health needs of affected communities at the heart of the political and peace processes that follow. This is a practical book and will be of particular interest to those planning for and responding to conflict-related disasters, policy makers, service commissioners and providers, politicians, civil servants and peace makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBombingszNorthern IrelandzOmagh. 0aPost-traumatic stress disorderxTreatmentzNorthern IrelandzOmagh. 0aPsychic traumaxTreatmentzNorthern IrelandzOmagh. 0aVictims of terrorismxServices forzNorthern IrelandzOmagh. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aBelfast Agreement.  aGood Friday agreement.  aNICTT.  aNorthern Ireland peace agreement.  aOmagh bombing.  aTroubles-focused response.  abusiness community.  acommunity's response.  amental health.  apeace-building project.  atrade union.  aviolent conflict.1 aBolton, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611639040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526116390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526116390/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles